 BRUSSELS, Oct 1 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A Belgian far-right sympathiser who went on a shooting rampage in Antwerp last year became the first person in Belgium to be tried on a new charge of murder with racist intent on Monday. Hans Van Themsche, 19, is accused of murdering a two-year-old white girl and her black nanny and attempting to kill a Turkish woman in May 2006. "For the first time in Belgium's judicial history, such motives are recognised in a murder case," said Edouard Delruelle, director of the Centre for Equal Opportunities and Opposition to Racism, a legal rights watchdog that is represented in the case. Those found guilty of murder face a sentence of three years to life and for attempted murder of three to 30 years. A racist motive would increase the minimum in each case to five years. The murders caused public consternation at the time as the then 18-year-old admitted wanting to kill foreigners and because members of his family belonged to far-right party Vlaams Belang. Vlaams Belang, which espouses anti-immigrant views and seeks independence for Dutch-speaking Flanders, has the largest presence in the region's parliament after winning 24 percent of the vote in 2004. On the opening day of the trial, which is set to last two weeks, a jury was sworn in and Van Themsche's lawyer lodged a motion to throw out the case after the indictment was leaked to the med
